<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: HUGE OIL RUNOFF INTO SANTA MONICA BAY FOUND 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Even though only eight inches of rain fell on the greater Los Angeles area in 
1989, storm drain runoff carried more than 4.4 million pounds of oil and grease 
into Santa Monica Bay, according to a study released Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
"We've got the equivalent of a major oil spill going into Santa Monica Bay 
every year because of this runoff," said Diane Cameron, an official with the 
Natural Resources Defense Council, the environmental group that did the study. 
</P>
<P>
The study also estimated that more than 522,000 pounds of zinc, 11,100 pounds 
of cadmium and 152,000 pounds of lead were swept into the bay because of 
runoff. Those amounts are far greater than the amounts deposited by the area's 
two major sewage plants, the study concluded. The levels should be viewed as 
"rough estimates," Cameron said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
