<P>
Glenfed Cuts Dividend: The parent of Glendale Federal Bank, California's 
third-largest thrift, slashed its quarterly dividend to 15 cents per share from 
30 cents. 
</P>
<P>
Glenfed Inc. said it cut the dividend as part of an effort to increase the 
amount of capital it generates internally. Federal capital standards for 
thrifts are set to rise in 1993. Glenfed also said the new dividend would be in 
line with the dividend yield paid by similar-sized thrifts. Before the 
announcement, Glenfed's dividend yield was 14. The new dividend will be payable 
Nov. 16 to stockholders of record on Nov. 5. Glenfed's stock closed at $7.50 a 
share, down 62.5 cents in NYSE trading. 
