<HEADLINE>
<P>
NATION; 
</P>
<P>
RARE WWII DIVE BOMBER SAVED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
CHICAGO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Navy has fished a rare World War II dive bomber from the depths of Lake 
Michigan and will display it at the National Museum of Naval Aviation in 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
The 32-foot SBD Douglas Dauntless, its guns still intact, was brought to the 
surface Tuesday about 16 miles off Chicago's Navy Pier, in 130 feet of water. 
</P>
<P>
Navy officials said the two-seat, single-engine plane is a rare find because 
there are fewer than 10 left. 
</P>
<P>
The plane sank Nov. 23, 1943, after the pilot missed a landing on the converted 
aircraft carrier Wolverine during a training mission, toppling from the 
carrier's deck into the water. The pilot was not injured. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, Divers watch as sunken plane is raised from Lake Michigan. Associated 
Press 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
