<P>
ORANGE JUICE PRICE FALL EXPECTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
LAKELAND, Fla. 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The state Department of Citrus reported today that the retail price for orange 
juice is expected to decline almost 12% during the coming year, while 
consumption of the juice is expected to increase by 15%. 
</P>
<P>
Robert Behr, economic research director of the Florida Department of Citrus, 
said he "expected retail prices to decline as a result of higher Florida orange 
production and record world orange juice supplies." 
</P>
<P>
Earlier this month, the U.S. Department of Agriculture estimated that Florida 
would produce 165 million boxes of oranges, a 50% increase over last season's 
freeze-damaged crop. 
</P>
</TEXT>
